Practice Questions
1) How do you think the speaker in ‘A Poison Tree’ feels about the downfall of their enemy?
Give at least two possibilities, explaining each with reference to the poem.
2) Compare how the poets create a sense of relentless movement in ‘The Destruction of Sennacherib’
and ‘The Charge of the Light Brigade’. Which poem do you think achieves this most successfully?
3) Analyse this quote from ‘The Prelude’, exploring its meaning and use of language techniques:
“o’er my thoughts / There hung a darkness, call it solitude / Or blank desertion.”
4) ‘Nature is the theme that consistently links Romantic poems.’
Do you think ‘A Poison Tree’, ‘The Destruction of Sennacherib’ and the extract from
‘The Prelude’ support this statement? Explain your answer with reference to the poems.
5) ‘In ‘The Man He Killed’, the line between friend and enemy is unclear.’
Do you agree with this statement? Explain your answer with reference to the poem.
6) Compare the ways in which the poets use punctuation in ‘The Man He Killed’ and ‘Belfast Confetti’
to create a sense of confusion. Which poem do you think uses punctuation most effectively?
7) ‘The central conflict in ‘Cousin Kate’ is between men and women, not the narrator and Kate.’
Do you agree with this statement? Explain your answer with reference to the poem.
8) Explain how the narrator of ‘Cousin Kate’ both conforms to and
challenges the 19th-century stereotype of the ‘fallen woman’.
9) ‘Biographical and historical context are essential to the interpretation of ‘Half-caste’.’
Do you agree with this statement? Explain your answer with reference to the poem.
10) Compare how the narrators of ‘Half-caste’ and ‘The Class Game’ use their negative
experiences of prejudice to teach others about their cultural identities.
11) ‘In ‘Exposure’, thinking about home does more harm than good to the soldiers.’
Do you agree with this statement? Explain your answer with reference to the poem.
Target Grade
These Target Grade 8-9 questions are designed to help you stretch your knowledge, think about the poems in
more depth and even see them in a new light — they’re the perfect way to take your essays to the next level.
